ned with MSEthe expectation of \(y_{t+1}\) conditional on \(x_t\). Proof. See Appendix 9.5. Proposition 8.8 Among the class of linear forecasts, the smallest MSE is obtained with the linear projection of \(y_{t+1}\) on \(x_t\). This projection, denoted by \(\hat{P}(y_{t+1}|x_t):= oldsymbol\alpha&#39;x_t\), satisfies: \[ egin{equation} \mathbb{E}\left( [y_{t+1} -  oldsymbol\alpha&#39;x_t]x_t ight)=\mathbf{0}.	ag{8.15} \end{equation}\] Proof. Consider the function \(f:\) \( oldsymbol\alpha ightarrow \mathbb{E}\left( [y_{t+1} -  oldsymbol\alpha&#39;x_t]^2 ight)\). We have: \[ f( oldsymbol\alpha) = \mathbb{E}\left( y_{t+1}^2 - 2 y_t x_t&#39; oldsymbol\alpha +  oldsymbol\alpha&#39;x_t x_t&#39; oldsymbol\alpha] ight). \] We have \(\partial f( oldsymbol\alpha)/\partial  oldsymbol\alpha = \mathbb{E}(-2 y_{t+1} x_t + 2 x_t x_t&#39; oldsymbol\alpha)\). The function is minimised for \(\partial f( oldsymbol\alpha)/\partial  oldsymbol\alpha =0\). Eq. (8.15) implies that \(\mathbb{E}\left( y_{t+1}x_t ight)=\mathbb{E}\left(x_tx_t&#39; ight) oldsymbol\alpha\). (Note that \(x_t x_t&#39; oldsymbol\alpha=x_t (x_t&#39; oldsymbol\alpha)=( oldsymbol\alpha&#39;x_t) x_t&#39;\).) Hence, if \(\mathbb{E}\left(x_tx_t&#39; ight)\) is nonsingular, \[ egin{equation}  oldsymbol\alpha=[\mathbb{E}\left(x_tx_t&#39; ight)]^{-1}\mathbb{E}\left( y_{t+1}x_t ight).	ag{8.16} \end{equation}\] The MSE then is: \[ \mathbb{E}([y_{t+1} -  oldsymbol\alpha&#39;x_t]^2) = \mathbb{E}{(y_{t+1}^2)} - \mathbb{E}\left( y_{t+1}x_t&#39; ight)[\mathbb{E}\left(x_tx_t&#39; ight)]^{-1}\mathbb{E}\left(x_ty_{t+1} ight). \] Consider the regression \(y_{t+1} =  oldsymbol eta&#39;\mathbf{x}_t + \varepsilon_{t+1}\). The OLS estimate is: \[ \mathbf{b} = \left[ \underbrace{  rac{1}{T} \sum_{i=1}^T \mathbf{x}_t\mathbf{x}_t&#39;}_{\mathbf{m}_1} ight]^{-1}\left[ \underbrace{  rac{1}{T} \sum_{i=1}^T \mathbf{x}_t&#39;y_{t+1}}_{\mathbf{m}_2} ight]. \] If \(\{x_t,y_t\}\) is covariance-stationary and ergodic for the second moments then the sample moments (\(\mathbf{m}_1\) and \(\mathbf{m}_2\)) converges in probability to the associated population moments and \(\mathbf{b} \overset{p}{ightarrow}  oldsymbol\alpha\) (where \( oldsymbol\alpha\) is defined in Eq. (8.16)). Example 8.3 (Forecasting an MA(q) process) Consider the MA(q) process: \[ y_t = \mu + \varepsilon_t + 	heta_1 \varepsilon_{t-1} + \dots + 	heta_q \varepsilon_{t-q}, \] where \(\{\varepsilon_t\}\) is a white noise sequence (Def. 8.1). We have:20 \[ egin{eqnarray*} &amp;&amp;\mathbb{E}(y_{t+h}|\varepsilon_{t},\varepsilon_{t-1},\dots) =\ &amp;&amp;\left\{  egin{array}{lll} \mu + 	heta_h \varepsilon_{t} + \dots + 	heta_q \varepsilon_{t-q+h} \quad &amp;for&amp; \quad h \in [1,q]\ \mu \quad &amp;for&amp; \quad h &gt; q \end{array} ight. \end{eqnarray*}\] and \[ egin{eqnarray*} &amp;&amp;\mathbb{V}ar(y_{t+h}|\varepsilon_{t},\varepsilon_{t-1},\dots)= \mathbb{E}\left( [y_{t+h} - \mathbb{E}(y_{t+h}|\varepsilon_{t},\varepsilon_{t-1},\dots)]^2 ight) =\ &amp;&amp;\left\{  egin{array}{lll} \sigma^2(1+	heta_1^2+\dots+	heta_{h-1}^2) \quad &amp;for&amp; \quad h \in [1,q]\ \sigma^2(1+	heta_1^2+\dots+	heta_q^2) \quad &amp;for&amp; \quad h&gt;q. \end{array} ight. \end{eqnarray*}\] Example 8.4 (Forecasting an AR(p) process) (See this web interface.) Consider the AR(p) process: \[ y_t = c + \phi_1 y_{t-1} + \phi_2 y_{t-2} + \dots + \phi_p y_{t-p} + \varepsilon_t, \] where \(\{\varepsilon_t\}\) is a white noise sequence (Def. 8.1). Using the notation of Eq. (8.9), we have: \[ \mathbf{y}_t -  oldsymbol\mu = F (\mathbf{y}_{t-1}-  oldsymbol\mu) +  oldsymbol\xi_t, \] with \( oldsymbol\mu = [\mu,\dots,\mu]&#39;\) (\(\mu\) is defined in Eq. (8.13)). Hence: \[ \mathbf{y}_{t+h} -  oldsymbol\mu =  oldsymbol\xi_{t+h} + F  oldsymbol\xi_{t+h-1} + \dots + F^{h-1}  oldsymbol\xi_{t+1} + F^h (\mathbf{y}_{t}- \mu). \] Therefore: \[ egin{eqnarray*} \mathbb{E}(\mathbf{y}_{t+h}|y_{t},y_{t-1},\dots) &amp;=&amp;  oldsymbol\mu + F^{h}(\mathbf{y}_t -  oldsymbol\mu)\ \m